<node id="&quot;CALCIUM&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Calcium is an element that, when bound, causes a structural change in proteins, increasing its alpha-helical content from 3 to 11%."&lt;SEP&gt;"Calcium is an element that, when bound, causes a structural change in proteins, increasing the alpha-helical content from 3 to 11%."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ALPHA-HELICAL CONTENT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Alpha-helical Content refers to the proportion of a protein's structure that is in the alpha-helical form, which increases from 3 to 11% upon binding calcium."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROTEIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Protein is a biological molecule that undergoes a structural change when calcium binds, increasing its alpha-helical content."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CARDIAC FORM OF CALSEQUESTRIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The cardiac form of calsequestrin is a specific type of calsequestrin that is more rapidly and extensively phosphorylated by Casein Kinase 2."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;GUT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Gut is the site within the body where calsequestrin is secreted to deprive bacteria of calcium ions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PHILANTHOTOXIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Philanthotoxin is a component of the venom of the Egyptian solitary wasp 'Philanthus triangulum', commonly known as the European beewolf."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 22}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 113}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PHILANTHUS TRIANGULUM&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Philanthus triangulum is the scientific name for the Egyptian solitary wasp, which produces philanthotoxins in its venom."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 22}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 113}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;EUROPEAN BEEWOLF&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"European Beewolf is an alternative name for the Egyptian solitary wasp 'Philanthus triangulum', which produces philanthotoxins in its venom."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;POLYAMINE TOXINS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Polyamine Toxins are a group of toxins found in the venom of wasps and spiders, characterized by their ability to immediately but reversibly paralyze prey."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;Δ-PHILANTHOTOXIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"δ-Philanthotoxin, also known as PhTX-433, is the most active philanthotoxin that can be refined from the venom of the European beewolf."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 8}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 60}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PHTX-433&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"PhTX-433 is a chemical compound used in research, specifically at the iGluR AMPA receptor in locust leg muscle."&lt;SEP&gt;"PhTX-433 is another name for δ-Philanthotoxin, a toxin that blocks excitatory neurotransmitter ion channels, including nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (NAChRs) and ionotropic glutamate receptors (iGluRs)."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0bc84126a758370eaed0363e620b208f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 8}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 60}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;EXCITATORY NEUROTRANSMITTER ION CHANNELS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Excitatory Neurotransmitter Ion Channels are channels that allow the passage of ions, such as sodium and calcium, in response to the binding of excitatory neurotransmitters like acetylcholine and glutamate."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 8}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 60}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NICOTINIC ACETYLCHOLINE RECEPTORS (NACHRS)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Nicotinic Acetylcholine Receptors (NAChRs) are specific types of ion channels that respond to the neurotransmitter acetylcholine and are blocked by philanthotoxins."&lt;SEP&gt;"Nicotinic Acetylcholine Receptors (NAChRs) are specific types of ion channels that respond to the neurotransmitter acetylcholine and are blocked by toxins like PhTX-433."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 8}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 59}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;IONOTROPIC GLUTAMATE RECEPTORS (IGLURS)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Ionotropic Glutamate Receptors (iGluRs) are another type of ion channel that responds to the neurotransmitter glutamate and are also blocked by toxins like PhTX-433."&lt;SEP&gt;"Ionotropic Glutamate Receptors (iGluRs) are another type of ion channel that responds to the neurotransmitter glutamate and are blocked by philanthotoxins."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 8}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 59}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;IC VALUE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"IC Value is a measure of the concentration of a toxin required to inhibit a certain percentage of a receptor's function, varying between analogues and receptor subunit composition."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 8}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 60}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LOCUST LEG MUSCLE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Locust Leg Muscle is the tissue where the IC value of PhTX-433 at the iGluR AMPA receptor is measured to be 18 μm."&lt;SEP&gt;"Locust leg muscle is the tissue in which the iGluR AMPA receptor is naturally expressed, relevant to the research involving PhTX-433."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0bc84126a758370eaed0363e620b208f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 8}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 60}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;RAT NERVE CELLS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Rat Nerve Cells are the tissue where the IC value of PhTX-433 at the rat nAChRs is measured to be 1 μm."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d515c1556efba0d3951a32073dbca790</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 8}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 60}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TOXIN&quot;">
